I"<p>I think the only time we ever had a Christmas tree in the house was when I was six.<!--more--> I remember that it shed a lot of needles. It probably smelled coniferous. It was one of those decisions that my parents made on a whim, because that’s what other people do, and wouldn’t it be fun to pretend to be like other people? We placed presents under the tree, like we did every year. But every other Christmas in my memory, we had to substitute for European/American tradition: a paper tree with cut-out diatom images as ornaments, which my mom found at work; the baby grand piano that left plenty of room for presents underneath; sometimes, simply the lights draped on the walls.</p>

<p>The way in which we celebrate holidays has always been eternally transforming. For a couple of years, we had barbecues on Fourth of July and then watched fireworks from the back deck. When I was in high school, my mom started making niangao (年糕) in the time of the new year, Gregorian or Chinese lunar. All of these activities were wonderful while they lasted, though indeed all of them came gradually to an end. As such, I have never come to really know an annual tradition. We simply always did things differently; in this sense my family was anti-traditional.</p>

<p>My first few days in Nepal have been a whirlwind of tradition. Our first day we wandered around the old city of Patan and parts of Lalitpur, where Priyankar lives; on the second, we trekked through 13.5 km of stupas, monasteries, and touristy spots; the third was the (beginning of the) culmination of a great Hindu Nepalese celebration called Dashain. In fact, the entire time I have been in Nepal has all been during festival season, when people visit their relatives in the village (or other parts of the city) and celebrate.</p>

<p>There is a different relationship between people and religion in the Kathmandu area compared to anywhere I have ever been. Shrines dot every street, every few shrines there is a monastery or temple, and in places one can find much larger stupas. Kathmandu is also home to the birthplace of Siddhartha Gautama, more generally referred to as the Shakyamuni Buddha. A lot of these religious establishments are Buddhist and some are Hindu, though I don’t fully understand the relationship between Hinduism and Buddhism here, since there are Hindu gods in Buddhist temples. (Disclaimer: I may be simply misunderstanding things, since Priyankar has tried to explain a lot to me, so I will not elaborate on this further.) Everywhere we go, Priyankar points out to me a lot of the architectural elements that come from more East Asian styles and those that come from South Asian styles. It reminds me a little bit of having immigrant roots, however distant they may be— we carry heritage with us that meets a new culture. I think in the US we constantly talk about cultural conflicts. Why do we rarely talk about the cultural harmonies? There is certainly some sort of religious harmony here. Maybe it is simply Priyankar’s open-mindedness that rubs off on me, but I get the vibe that religions coexist quite well here.</p>

<p>Dashain is specifically a Hindu holiday but nearly the entire city shuts down—nine out of ten shop fronts we walk by are closed; buses rarely run or cease running altogether; traffic clears up; everyone posts a notice that says “sorry, but we’re closed for Dashain until [some date], happy Dashain!”The city retreats into home-festival mode, during which I was fortunate to join Priyankar’s family for some of the celebrations.</p>

<p>On Friday, we went first thing in the morning to Priyankar’s paternal relatives. The living room was filled with about fifteen people. I met a lot of people and then it all began, which I will try to explain: one by one, a person in the room would approach the elder at the front; the elder would press rice mixed in red tikka onto the relative’s forehead and place wheatgrass on their head (or tucked behind the ear, or placed in one’s hat). First the priest blessed the elders, and then the elders would bless anyone who was younger than them, and then this would continue in decreasing order of age such that the small children were blessed by everyone. The younger relative received money from the elder alongside the blessing. (In practice, it seemed like only the kids actually received money… and it was a lot of money!) Priyankar was actually one of the youngest people there, so he only blessed one person, his younger cousin. His paternal grandmother blessed me, and his mother insisted on blessing me too. Then we went to the home of his maternal grandparents, and went through the same ritual, though there were far fewer people there.</p>

<p>That same day, Priyankar disappeared several times to go to many other relatives’ houses. Meanwhile, I did some birdwatching from the roof, read some introductory Buddhism, and drank tea. We didn’t participate much in the festivities the following day, though the day after we rejoined them. I washed off the second round of red tikka a few hours ago. Each time I was blessed, I felt like I was doing some part of the whole procedure wrong! (It is generally true that I was, but I told myself, it’s not about the doing, it’s about the feeling, you know?)</p>

<p>Nonetheless, I was thankful to be included in the celebrations, the foreign guest, sometimes observer and a welcome participant. It makes me wonder what it would be like to have traditions like this in my family, or feel like the traditions in my family belonged to a broader cultural heritage. When one is surrounded by the familiar and one knows what to expect from the future— I think these feelings form a semblance of “home.” But I am beholden to my constant cravings for new ideas and experiences. I wonder if that will change.</p>

<p>Other news:
1) We are leaving for the mountains tomorrow! Langtang Valley, here we come. We will be out for 8 days. I think I have packed too much. Such will be my first backpacking trip. (Note on “mountains”: Pripri always laughed at mountains in the US, especially in Connecticut; now I understand why…)</p>

<p>2) I washed my clothes by hand for the first time. I know, city boy! But this feels like a big deal for me. Now I am a real adult?</p>

<p>3) I am officially staying in Nepal until November 12th, so I will catch part of one more festival here before I head off to Kunming (China). I will also visit Lumbini, the birthplace of Shakyamuni Buddha, and Pokhara, the other tourist magnet of Nepal.</p>

<p>4) I am reading a book that Priyankar bought called “An Introduction to Buddhism”. I think I will have some downtime in the mountains. Reflections on this will come another time.</p>

<p>5) Shoutout to everyone who reached out to me last time!!! I am super happy to hear from all of you. Invitation is still open.</p>

<p>Love from thin air,
Rain</p>
